                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JAMES RICHARDS</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18350406-1108-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18350406-1108-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18350406-1108-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp>for stealing, on the <rs id="t18350406-cd-213" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18350406-1108-offence-1 t18350406-cd-213"></join>12th of March</rs>, 8 yards of diaper, value 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 14 yards of linen-cloth, value 35<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 handkerchief, value 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 2 pair of socks, value 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 table cover, value 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 shirt, value 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; and 12 yards of silk, value 32<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18350406-name-1385" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18350406-name-1385" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350406-name-1385" type="surname" value="SERJEANT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350406-name-1385" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18350406-1108-offence-1 t18350406-name-1385"></join>William Serjeant</persName> and another, his masters.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350406-name-1386" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350406-name-1386" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350406-name-1386" type="surname" value="NICHOLSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350406-name-1386" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD NICHOLSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a draper, in partnership with William Ser<lb></lb>jeant; the prisoner was in our employ five or six years—I have our book here, in which is entered, in the prisoner's writing, "Mrs. Bennett, Trinity-square, remnant of Irish, 18<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., on approbation;" meaning it was to be left there, and if not approved to be returned; and against it is written "Rd.;" signifying returned—it was not returned; and I asked the prisoner what had become of the Irish that he had taken away a few days before—he said it had been sent to Mrs. Bennett and returned; he had brought it</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183504060216"></xptr>
               <p>back himself, and he was willing to satisfy me by going to Mrs. Bennett—I then said, "I had been to Mrs. Bennett"—the prisoner then said, he had taken it and sold it to make up his rent—I went to his premises, in Union-street, where I found this damask and some other articles—I know this damask—I have the pattern at home.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> I believe he stated the circum<lb></lb>stances under which he took these things? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; he said he took it, in consequence of distress—he has a wife and two children—he left our ser<lb></lb>vice about six months ago, and applied to be taken back.</p>
               <p>(John Morris, of Walnut-tree-walk, Lambeth; Thomas England, a brush-maker, of Union-street; Mr. Price, a cabinet-maker, of New Park-street; and Mr. Webb, a draper, of the Borough; gave the prisoner a good character; the latter of whom promised to find him employ.)</p>
               <p>
